# Reducer.elm — WORKHORSE (pure action reducer)

Renamed from `Replay.elm` 2026-04-21 because the name was
misleading: this module is the shared pure reducer used by
both live play AND replay, not a replay-specific thing.

Given a `WireAction` and a `(board, hand)` state, produce the
next state. That's it. Nothing UI-layer here.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE. Small, pure, stable.
- **Role in one-action-log invariant:** `applyAction` is the
  canonical fold over the Elm-side action log. Replay, undo
  (future), and live-play walkers all advance state through
  this one reducer.
- **Sole owner of physics (2026-04-21):** `Main.Apply.applyAction`
  used to re-implement the five physics branches. Post-DRY,
  Apply delegates to this module and keeps only the Model-level
  wrappers (Score, cardsPlayedThisTurn, CompleteTurn via Game,
  status text).

## Key exports

- `State` — `{ board : List CardStack, hand : Hand }`.
- `initialState : State` — dealt from `Dealer.initialBoard` +
  `Dealer.openingHand`. Starting point for replay if no
  session-specific baseline is provided.
- `applyAction : WireAction -> State -> State` — the reducer.

## The 7 WireAction branches

Mirrors `WireAction.elm` exactly (wire is primitives-only as of
2026-04-20). Handled:
- **`Split`** — delegates to `GestureArbitration.applySplit`.
- **`MergeStack`** — looks up both stacks, tries
  `BoardActions.tryStackMerge`, applies the resulting
  `BoardChange` or no-ops.
- **`MergeHand`** — looks up target stack, resolves the hand
  card (see "opponent-hand fallback" below), tries
  `BoardActions.tryHandMerge`, applies or no-ops.
- **`PlaceHand`** — resolves the hand card, applies
  `BoardActions.placeHandCard`, removes from hand.
- **`MoveStack`** — applies `BoardActions.moveStack`.

No-ops (intentional):
- **`CompleteTurn`** — turn boundary, not physics. Replay
  here doesn't model turn-level score; that's a caller
  concern.
- **`Undo`** — deferred in V1 replay; if one ever shows up in
  a log, we no-op rather than crash.

## LOAD-BEARING: opponent-hand fallback on `MergeHand`

When replaying a log that contains the OPPONENT's moves, the
opponent's hand was dealt server-side and never sent to this
client. The `handCard` reference in a `MergeHand` action
names a card we don't have in `state.hand`.

The fix: if `findHandCard` returns Nothing, fall back to a
synthetic `HandCard { card = ..., state = HandNormal }` and
skip the hand-update step (`mutateHand = False`). The board
still advances; we just don't try to remove from a hand we
never knew.

Without this, replay of a two-player game breaks on every
opponent `MergeHand`. The flag `mutateHand` is how we avoid
silently corrupting the tracked player's hand when we mean
"skip this update."

## What this module deliberately does NOT do

- **Turn-level scoring.** No-op on `CompleteTurn`. Caller
  (Game.applyCompleteTurn) owns that.
- **Referee validation.** Replay assumes the log was already
  validated at recording time.
- **Undo.** V1 treats Undo as no-op; if Undo is wanted in
  replay, it needs a bidirectional action representation
  that doesn't exist yet.
- **Initial state from server.** `initialState` is the local
  fallback; the real session-specific baseline is loaded by
  `Main/Wire` from `/sessions/:id/actions` and fed in.

## Internal helpers

`removeStackOnce`, `removeHandCardByContent`, `listAt`,
`applyChange`, `findHandCard` — ~6 LOC total. Post-DRY
(2026-04-21), these live only here; `Main.Apply` no longer
keeps its own copies. If another module ever needs the same
primitives, promote to a shared helper then.

## Pointers

- Depends on: `WireAction`, `BoardActions`, `CardStack`,
  `Hand`, `GestureArbitration`, `Dealer`, `Card`.
- Consumer: `Main/Apply.applyAction` (wraps this with
  Msg plumbing), `Main/State.replayBaseline` logic.
- Tests: `tests/Game.ReducerTest.elm`.

